Q: Auto Resize Font to fit rectangle A: <p>It's been a while but I came across this issue.
MSDN offers a sample with a GetAdjustedFont method to help with this process:</p>
<p><em>(shamelessly stolen from <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150110030457/http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb986765.aspx" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb986765.aspx)</a></em></p>
<pre><code>public Font GetMaximumFontSize(Graphics g, string graphicString, Font originalFont, int containerWidth, int maxFontSize, int minFontSize, bool smallestOnFail)
{
   Font testFont = null;
   // We utilize MeasureString which we get via a control instance           
   for (int adjustedSize = maxFontSize; adjustedSize &gt;= minFontSize; adjustedSize--)
   {
      testFont = new Font(originalFont.Name, adjustedSize, originalFont.Style);

      // Test the string with the new size
      SizeF adjustedSizeNew = g.MeasureString(graphicString, testFont);

      if (containerWidth &gt; Convert.ToInt32(adjustedSizeNew.Width))
      {
         // Good font, return it
         return testFont;
      }
   }

   // If you get here there was no fontsize that worked
   // return minimumSize or original?
   if (smallestOnFail)
   {
      return testFont;
   }
   else
   {
      return originalFont;
   }
}
</code></pre>

Q: When I copy-paste a block of code more than 3 to 4 times, sometimes I forget to change the variables. How to avoid this issue? A: <p>When you copy a code as follows:</p>
<pre><code>var a1 = b1.substring(0,50) + c1;
</code></pre>
<p>Remove the variable part of the line like this:</p>
<pre><code>var a = b.substring(0,50) + c;
</code></pre>
<p>Then copy as many times as needed like this:</p>
<pre><code>var a = b.substring(0,50) + c;
var a = b.substring(0,50) + c;
var a = b.substring(0,50) + c;
</code></pre>
<p>Then update the code after copying like this:</p>
<pre><code>var a1 = b1.substring(0,50) + c1;
var a2 = b2.substring(0,50) + c2;
var a3 = b3.substring(0,50) + c3;
</code></pre>
<p>In this way (removing the changeable part before copying) you will be able to overcome possible copy-pasting related error. And you will be forgot to change essential texts.</p>

Q: Why is my top div element not as wide as the other two in my media query? A: <p>the problem is no width is specified, it could be 1px as well, to your .pricing-plan class set width to 100%</p>
<pre><code>.pricing-plan {
    background-color: lightgray;
    text-align: center;
    border-radius: 5px;
    padding: 20px;
    max-width: 400px;
    flex: 1;
    width: 100%; /* add this */
}
</code></pre>
<p>this would max to 400px, and below that would take 100%</p>

Q: How to detect if there&#39;s a Windows Update available using Delphi code? A: <p>There is a COM object in Windows, named <code>Microsoft.Update.Session</code>, that you can query, with parameters for online/offline check (and more).</p>
<p>Here is a function that checks for updates (either a full online check, or just an offline check of whether some updates are already pending), and optionally also fills in a string list with the available update names:</p>
<pre class="lang-pascal prettyprint-override"><code>uses 
  System.SysUtils,
  Winapi.ActiveX,
  System.Win.ComObj,
  System.Variants;

// Meaning of the WithOnlineCheck parameter:
//   False = do NOT go online, 
//   True = check online (may take long time)
// UpdateInfo, if passed in, gets filled
// with the titles of the available updates
function AreWindowsUpdatesAvailable(WithOnlineCheck: Boolean;
  UpdateInfo: TStrings = nil): Boolean;
var
  Criteria: string;
  UpdateSession: OleVariant;  // Microsoft.Update.Session
  UpdateSearcher: OleVariant;  // IUpdateSearcher
  SearchResult: OleVariant;  // ISearchResult
begin
  // These criteria mirror what the Windows &quot;Settings&quot; app UI would show
  Criteria := 'IsInstalled=0 and IsHidden=0 and IsAssigned=1';

  UpdateSession  := CreateOleObject('Microsoft.Update.Session');

  // (Optional) client ID
  UpdateSession.ClientApplicationID := 'Delphi application check';

  UpdateSearcher := UpdateSession.CreateUpdateSearcher;
  UpdateSearcher.Online := WithOnlineCheck; 

  SearchResult := UpdateSearcher.Search(Criteria);

  Result := (not VarIsNull(SearchResult)) and 
            (SearchResult.Updates.Count &gt; 0);

  // Optionally return the titles of the updates
  if Result and (UpdateInfo &lt;&gt; nil) then
  begin
    UpdateInfo.Clear;
    for i := 0 to SearchResult.Updates.Count - 1 do
    begin
      Update := SearchResult.Updates[i];
      UpdateInfo.Add(Update.Title);
    end;
  end;
end;
</code></pre>
<p>Remember to call <code>CoInitialize(nil)</code> somewhere at startup of the program (for example in some <code>initialization</code> section) and <code>CoUninitialize</code> when the program closes (for example in the corresponding <code>finalization</code> section), unless the program is a VCL application (VCL applications make these calls for you).</p>
